subject: yosemitev2:Multi-host DIMM info displayed in OCP debug card
commitMessage:
yosemitev2:Multi-host DIMM info displayed in OCP debug card

This implementation is going to display the DIMM
information in the OCP debug-card.

Tested: information frame value of Dimm info
displayed in the OCP debug card with multi-host
Yosemitev2 platform.

I have a few suggestions on how to enable the code to scale beyond just YV2 plus provide clarity to things like dimm vendors.

Instead of just labeling the DIMM types generically (as 1, 2, 3), it would be better to label the DIMM types since these align with real vendor names.  For instance, DIMM_TYPE1 might better be labeled as DIMM_TYPE_SAMSUNG.  In the event a vendor can have multiple types, it might be better to use DIMM_TYPE_SAMSUNG_CE.

Would recommend building a table of the names and indexes to ensure this code scales.  On other systems, MEMxx names are different and map to slots which may not be at the same index.  Placement of the table should be in the platform specific code so the common code can just use the table to build these strings.
While not part of this patch, we should remove this commented out code as a separate patch.  It should not have been merged.
Please add a map for these.
Don't we have some common place to put these?  It seems very unusual to have some stray IPMI command numbers sprinkled in the middle of this file.
This is likely very particular to Yv2.  How do we extend the names for other systems?

Okay, I have the logic implementation for this, which is to introduce a platform-specific JSON for each machine based on that we can identify dimm_type names and load them in /etc/oemData.json
directly is this fine?
Is this name used elsewhere already?  Why are they inconsistently named (ie. dimmType vs dimm_type)?
Why are you comparing a length with NULL?  (You should never see 'NULL' in C++ code anyhow, but nullptr).

I'm almost certain there is a way to specify the parameters in here so that the IPMI code will automatically parse out fields into parameters for us.  Can we please refactor this accordingly for at least mfgId, dimmIndex, paramSel?
Code needs a rebase as well.
I see no change having been done here.  reinterpret_cast is almost never safe to do.
could you please suggest exactly what you are mentioning here (automatic parsing)?

Please take a look at `ipmiSetSensorReading` and `ipmiSenGetSensorReading` in phosphor-host-ipmid/dbus-sdr/sensorcommands.cpp for an example of what I'm talking about.  Both of these functions use automatic parsing and automatic formulation of the response.
A few issues still need clarification in this latest patchset.  Thanks!
Is there a specific reason why 150 was chosen?  Would like to understand the logic as 150 seems an odd choice for a max buffer size.
There is no specific reason for bus size as 150, based on the requirement will change in next patch set thanks.

Is there a way to push this to the platform config as different platforms will have different numbers of DIMMs which may not be numbered in the same way.  I would prefer this not be hard-coded when we will need to extend this to other platforms.

Technically, isn't some of the DIMM information available when data.push_back(result) is executed above?  Thus, it would be good to report some DIMM data is available if at least some of the DIMM data has been processed prior to an exception as opposed to logging an error that DIMM information not available.  Thus, if an error occurred on say the 3rd or 4th DIMM, it would still be helpful to attempt to continue for other DIMMs and report just the DIMM that caused the failure as having no DIMM information available.
Is there a need to do this test twice here and not combine the code under a single if statement?
yes correct, i'll update that too.
Byte 1..48 –Product name(ASCII code) to manage this product name less than 50 is not sufficient.
Please add a comment in the code as to why 50 was chosen then.
@Michael, can you confirm your concerns have been resolved?
